Since the `MissingInfoNamespace` is actually raised by `self._require_namespace(...)`, I think it would be nicer to do the following (minimal branching, and at most one exception raised):

```python
@property
def modified(self):
    namespace =  "modified" if "modified" in self.raw else "details"
    self._require_namespace(namespace)
    return self._make_datetime(self.get(namespace, "modified"))
```

I looked at the implementation of `PyInterpreterState_Get()` (below for easy reference), it has a path to set the Python error indicator. I think it's best to have `if` below here, to not clobber reporting of the root cause of the failure, but also because we have `assert(!PyErr_Occurred());` in `pybind11_fail()`:

```
if (PyErr_Occurred()) {
    throw error_already_set();
}
```

I'm not sure if we still need `if (!state_dict)` in the next line.

Maybe easiest and best:
```
if (PyErr_Occurred() || !state_dict) {
    throw error_already_set();
}
```

If there is an unexpected inconsistency, `error_already_set()` [will tell us clearly](https://github.com/pybind/pybind11/blob/0176632e8cef72a4223f2df54d6dfb9e552ec71f/include/pybind11/pytypes.h#L451-L454).

We could use [`raise_from(PyExc_SystemError, "get_internals(): could not acquire state dictionary!")`](https://github.com/pybind/pybind11/blob/0176632e8cef72a4223f2df54d6dfb9e552ec71f/include/pybind11/pytypes.h#L688)  (untested) but maybe that's overkill?

```
PyInterpreterState *
PyInterpreterState_Get(void)
{
    PyThreadState *tstate = _PyThreadState_GET();
    _Py_EnsureTstateNotNULL(tstate);
    PyInterpreterState *interp = tstate->interp;
    if (interp == NULL) {
        Py_FatalError("no current interpreter");
    }
    return interp;
}
```

