> @captainsafia do you have anything written on the UX of supporting multiple different editors?

No exactly this but I can explain it here.

> I see there is a configuration option for it already in, but is it already possible to use it?

Yes. It is possible to use it.

> Also, is it does it only affect code cells, or also markdown cells? 

It affects all cell types.

Here's a breakdown of how it works.

We start off in @nteract/stateful-components. That's the package that we use to render everything nowadays. In particular, the [Editor](https://github.com/nteract/nteract/blob/master/packages/stateful-components/src/inputs/editor.tsx) component reads from the `state.config.editorType` property and selects the editor to render from its children. It should be implemented like this.

```js
import Editor from "@nteract/stateful-components";

<Editor id={id} contentRef={contentRef}>
{
     {
        codemirror: (props: PassedEditorProps) => (
          <ConnectedCodeMirrorEditor {...props} />
        ),
        ace: (props: PassedEditorProps) => (<ConnectedAceEditor {...props}/>
      }
}
</Editor>
```

`PassedEditorProps` is a set of props that are common (or relatively common) across all editors. These are things like the `value` which represents the contents of the editor and `editorFocused`. The `Editor` component is responsible for mapping these properties from the Redux store and passing them to the one of the child editors that is rendered.

To this end, I am imagining that if we group editor configurations by editor type then we can do something like this in the `mapStateToProps` of the editor.

```
function mapStateToProps(props: OwnProps) {
   const editorType = state.config.editorType;
   // All the config associated with this particular editor
   const config = state.config.get(editorType);
   return {
     ...
     config
      ...
    };
}
```

With this change, `config` would be a property in the `PassedEditorProps` interface so that each editor will receive a `config` object from the parent that matches its config options.

