The one thing I don't like about this API is that if you wanna build a new string with `from_parts` I think you'll still need to specify the encoding.

```rust
// is this multipart or double null terminated?
let x = SbpString::from_parts(["a", "b", "c"]);
// will have to do something like
let x = SbpString::<_, Multipart>::from_parts(["a", "b", "c"]);
```

Not sure if there is a nice way around that, other than by naming the functions differently. Also something to consider is adding `FromIterator` impls for the multipart strings

```rust
impl<T: AsRef<[u8]>> FromIterator<T> for SbpString<Vec<u8>, Multipart> {
    fn from_iter<I: IntoIterator<Item=T>>(iter: I) -> Self {
        todo!();
    }
}
```

which would let people use `.collect` to create multipart strings

```rust
let parts = ["a", "b", "c"];
let string: SbpString<_, Multipart> = parts.into_iter().collect();
```

Could just do that instead of `from_parts` (or could do both and impl one via the other)

> and have parts_to_vec as a helper method to parse iterator according to the nulls, return an error if the number of nulls dont match?

Creating the string from the parts should be something like 

```rust
fn from_parts(it: ...) -> Self {
    // check that none of the parts contain a null byte already
    // and return an error (I think a case could also be made to panic instead, or we could have the code
    // remove the null bytes) 
    // once you've checked it just
    Self {
        data: it.intersperse(b"0").collect(),
        encoding: PhantomData,
    }
}
```

